  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you delete all photos from your iPhone?",
  "response": "To delete all photos from your iPhone, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Using the Photos app:**\n   - Open the **Photos** app on your iPhone.\n   - Go to the **Albums** tab at the bottom.\n   - Open the **All Photos** album.\n   - Tap **Select** at the top right corner.\n   - Tap and hold on a photo, then swipe to select all photos. Alternatively, you can tap **Select All** if this option is available.\n   - Tap the trash icon (\ud83d\uddd1\ufe0f) to move the selected photos to the **Recently Deleted** album.\n   - Confirm by tapping **Delete Photos**.\n   - Go to the **Albums** tab again.\n   - Open the **Recently Deleted** album.\n   - Tap **Select** and choose **Delete All** at the bottom to permanently remove all photos.\n   - Confirm by tapping **Delete Photos**.\n\n2. **Using iCloud (if photos are synced):**\n   - Ensure photos are synced with iCloud on your iPhone.\n   - Access iCloud on a computer by visiting [iCloud.com](https://www.icloud.com/).\n   - Log in with your Apple ID.\n   - Select **Photos**.\n   - Click on one photo, then press **Cmd+A** (Mac) or **Ctrl+A** (Windows) to select all photos.\n   - Click the trash icon to delete them.\n   - Confirm deletion.\n\n3. **Using Mac and Finder (macOS Catalina and later):**\n   - Connect your iPhone to your Mac using a USB cable.\n   - Open **Finder** and select your iPhone from the sidebar.\n   - Go to the **Photos** tab.\n   - Select all photos and click **Delete**.\n\n4. **Using Windows and File Explorer:**\n   - Connect your iPhone to your PC using a USB cable.\n   - Open **File Explorer** and go to your iPhone under **Devices and Drives**.\n   - Navigate to **Internal Storage > DCIM**.\n   - Select all photo folders and delete them.\n\nRemember, deleting all photos is permanent and cannot be undone, so make sure you've backed up any important photos before proceeding.",
